{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584729"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:55:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:55:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14791"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14791"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.03,0.06,0.15,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7482"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66987"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7482"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14791"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52441"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5149"},{"type":"tags","id":"7065"},{"type":"tags","id":"8412"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22403"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66987"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents with lower urinary tract symptoms including hesitancy, weak stream, and nocturia. Digital rectal examination reveals an enlarged, smooth prostate. The diagnosis of benign prostatic hyperplasia is made. A decision is made to treat him with tamsulosin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action for this agent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks alpha-1 adrenergic receptors in prostatic smooth muscle","Blocks muscarinic receptors in the bladder","Increases bladder muscle contractility","Inhibits 5-alpha reductase enzyme activity","Reduces testosterone production in the testes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBenign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) can be treated with several medication classes that work through different mechanisms. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-1 adrenergic receptor antagonists\u003C/strong\u003E like tamsulosin work by \u003Cstrong\u003Erelaxing smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E in the prostate and bladder neck, improving urinary flow. This is often used as first-line therapy due to rapid symptom improvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5-alpha reductase inhibitors like finasteride prevent the conversion of testosterone to dihydrotestosterone by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting 5-alpha reductase enzyme activity\u003C/strong\u003E, gradually reducing prostate size over months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing bladder contractility\u003C/strong\u003E would not help BPH and could worsen symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscarinic receptor antagonists\u003C/strong\u003E (anticholinergics) can help with symptoms of overactive bladder but are not first-line for the treatment of BPH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReducing \u003Cstrong\u003Etestosterone production\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism used for BPH treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alpha-1 receptor antagonists relax prostatic smooth muscle to improve urinary flow in benign prostatic hyperplasia","5-alpha reductase inhibitors block conversion of testosterone to dihydrotestosterone to reduce prostate size","Anticholinergics reduce bladder muscle contractions but are not first-line for benign prostatic hyperplasia"],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52441"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14791"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52441"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T10:13:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T10:14:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7482"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66987"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"